l-new footage featuring Hayley Mills will be included. Additional interviewees include Tom Skerritt, Carrie Kei Heim, Creel triplets including, Monica Creel Lacy, Leanna & Joy Creel, Susan Henning, Ron Maxwell (Director of ''Parent Trap II'', Mollie Miller (Director of ''Parent Trap III''/''Hawaiian Honeymoon''), Tommy Sands, and Joanna Barnes and even Lynette Winters, and Kay Cole (camp inch scenes). [[Bridgette Andersen]]'s Teresa mother discusses reflections on experiences that occurred on-set during filming of ''The Parent Trap II'', with director Ron Maxwell, among others. Marilyn McCoo also is featured sharing memories about recording music for ''Parent Trap II''. Charles Fox who wrote the theme, \"Let's Get What We Got\" that was the title music in the opening for \"The Parent Trap II\", and the entire music score. He is also featured on-camera, with talking about his experiences in the music.  \n\nThe project will analyze and also focus on the life of Erich Kastner who wrote the original German book, ''[[Lottie and Lisa|Das Doppelte Lottchen]]''  that the films were based on. Luke Springman, German professor Aaron Pacentine will executive produce the film. This is the first full-length film documentary that details coverage on the 1980s Parent Trap films, and the first time the director, Mollie Miller, has spoken out publicly about the original film since then.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Lottie and Lisa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parent Trap (film series), The}}\n[[Category:The Parent Trap films| ]]\n[[Category:Comedy film series]]\n[[Category:Children's film series]]\n[[Category:Films about twin sisters]]\n[[Category:Disney film series]]\n[[Category:Film series introduced in 1961]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilms", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Parent_Trap_(film_series)"}
{"title_page": "List of federal political parties in Canada", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{original research|date=January 2019}}\n{{more citations needed|date=November 2018}}\n}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=April 2020}}\nIn contrast with the political party systems of many nations, Canadian political parties at the federal level are often only loosely connected with parties at the provincial level, despite having similar names and policy positions.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Christian|first1=William|last2=Jansen|first2=Harold|title=Party System|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/party-system|website=The Canadian Encyclopedia |publisher=Historica Canada|accessdate=November 7, 2018|date=December 11, 2015|quote=Although there are often provincial parties with similar names or aims as national political parties, Canadian parties are not generally well-integrated... Despite the general lack of formal ties, however, there is often significant overlap between supporters of provincial and national parties of the same name.}}</ref> One exception is the [[New Democratic Party]], which is organizationally integrated with most of its provincial counterparts including a shared membership.\n\n==Current parties==\nThese are all of the political parties registered with [[Elections Canada]] or eligible to run candidates in federal elections as of April 2020.<ref name=\"ECparties\">{{Cite web |last=Elections Canada |url=http://elections.ca/content.aspx?section=pol&dir=par&document=index&lang=e |title=Registered Political Parties and Parties Eligible for Registration |work=[[Elections Canada]] |date=April 7, 2020 |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Colspan=\"2\"| Name\n! Founded\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Ideology{{Original research inline|date=January 2019}}\n\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Leader\n! [[House of Commons of Canada|MPs]]\n! Most MPs (numerically)\n! Most MPs (proportionally)\n! [[Senate of Canada|Senators]]\n! Political position\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|row}}\n| '''[[Liberal Party of Canada]]'''<br /><small>{{lang|fr|Parti lib\u00e9ral du Canada}}</small>\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 1867\n| [[Liberalism in Canada|Liberalism]], [[social liberalism]]\n| [[Justin Trudeau]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 157\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 184 (2015)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 73% (1940)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0 <!--- There are no more Liberal Party of Canada senators, the Senate Liberal Caucus is organizationally and politically independent of the party -->\n| [[Centre left]]\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Conservative|row}}\n| '''[[Conservative Party of Canada]]'''&nbsp;<br /><small>{{lang|fr|Parti conservateur du Canada}}</small>\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 2003\n| [[Conservatism in Canada|Conservatism]], [[economic liberalism]], [[fiscal conservatism]]\n| [[Andrew Scheer]] \n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 121\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 166 (2011)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 54% (2011)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 24\n| [[Centre right]]\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|BQ|row}}\n| {{lang|fr|'''[[Bloc Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]]'''}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 1991\n| [[Quebec sovereignty movement|Quebec sovereignty]], [[social democracy]], [[Regionalism (politics)|regionalism]]\n| [[Yves-Fran\u00e7ois Blanchet]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 32\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 54 (1993)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 18% (1993)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0\n| [[Centre left]]\n|-\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|NDP|row}}\n| '''[[New Democratic Party]]'''<br /><small>{{lang|fr|Nouveau Parti d\u00e9mocratique}}</small>\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 1961\n|  [[Social democracy]], [[progressivism]] <!--No citations at party's article for democratic socialism as ideology -->\n| [[Jagmeet Singh]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 24\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 103 (2011)\n| style=\"tex