l (Unionist)]]\n|1917||1921\n|Members of the Liberal Party who supported [[Robert Borden]]'s coalition government.\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 11 (1917)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 5% (1917)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 4 (1919)\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|[[Parti canadien (1942)|Parti canadien]]\n|1942||????\n|anti-conscription\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 1 (1942)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| {{sort|0.5|<1% (1942)}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Independent|row}}\n|'' [[Qu\u00e9bec debout|Qu\u00e9bec debout/Groupe parliamentaire qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]]''\n|2018||{{dts|2018}}\n|Formed when several MPs left the [[Bloc Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]] due to the leadership of [[Martine Ouellet]]. Rejoined after she lost a leadership review vote and resigned.\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 7 (2018)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 2% (2018)\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0\n{{Canadian party colour|CA|Liberal|row}}\n| ''[[Senate Liberal Caucus]]'' <br /><small>{{lang|fr|Caucus lib\u00e9ral du S\u00e9nat}}</small>\n| 2014\n| 2019\n| [[Liberalism in Canada|Liberalism]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 0\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 32 (2014)\n|}\n\n=== Historical designations used by single candidates ===\n* Nationalist Liberal (Fleming Blanchard McCurdy), 1920 \u2014 McCurdy won a by-election under the Nationalist Liberal designation, but sat with the [[National Liberal and Conservative Party]] caucus\n* Protectionist (Joseph-\u00c9douard Moranville), 1926\n* Franc Lib (I) (Alfred Edward Watts), 1930\n* [[Prohibition Party (Canada)|Prohibition Party]] (Edwin Clarke Appleby), 1930\n* ''[[National Unity Party (Canada)|Parti national social chr\u00e9tien]]'' (Robert Rae Manville), 1934\u20131940\n* Anti-Communist (I) (Jean Tissot), 1935\n* [[Verdun (candidate)|Verdun]] (Herv\u00e9 Ferland), 1935\n* Veterans Party (Alloys Reginald Sprenger), 1935\n* Technocrat (Joseph McCrae Newman), 1935\n* Anti-Conscriptionist ([[Louis-G\u00e9rard Gosselin]]), 1940\n* [[Social Credit-National Unity]] (Harry Watson Arnold), 1940\n* [[National-Unity (candidate)|National-Unity]] (Robert Rae Manville), 1940\n* Trades Union (Nigel Morgan), 1945\n* [[Autonomist candidate]] (Paul Mass\u00e9), 1947\n* Christian Liberal (Howard A. Prentice), 1953\n* ''Locataire'' ([[Louis Seigneur]]), 1953\n* Anti-Communist (II) (Patrick Walsh), 1953\n* [[Canadian Democrat]] (Gerry Goeujon), 1957\n* [[National Credit Control]] (John Bernard Ball), 1957\n* ''Capital familial'' (Henri-Georges Grenier), 1957\u20131962\n* Liberal Conservative Coalition (George Rolland), 1957\n* ''[[Parti ouvrier canadien]]'' (Jean-Jacques Rouleau), 1958\n* [[League for Socialist Action]], 1961\u20131977\n* [[Co-operative Builders of Canada]] (Edgar-Bernard Charron), 1962\n*[[All Canadian Party]] (John Darby Naismith), 1962\u20131962\n* ''Parti humain familial'' (Henri-Georges Grenier), 1964\n* ''Droit vital personnel'' (Henri-Georges Grenier), 1965\n* [[Progressive Workers Movement]] (Jerry Le Bourdais), 1965\n* ''Esprit Social'' (Henri-Georges Grenier), 1967\u20131971\n* [[Work Less Party]] ([[Betty Krawczyk]]), 2007\u20132010\n* Franc Lib (II) (Jean-Roger Marcotte), 1968\n* [[Party for Accountability, Competency and Transparency]] (formerly Online Party) (Michael Nicula), 2012\u20132016<ref name=\"Party for Accountability, Competency and Transparency Deregistered\">{{cite web|title=Deregistration of Western Block Party|url=http://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=pol&dir=par&document=index&lang=e#pact|publisher=Elections Canada}}</ref>\n* National Socialist ([[Martin K. Weiche]]), 1968\n* [[New Canada Party]] (Fred Reiner), 1968\n* [[Nationalist Party of Canada]] (Bob Smith), founded 1977\n* [[Christian Democrat Party of Canada]] (Sydney Thompson), 1981\n* [[Work Less Party]] (Betty Krawczyk), 2007\u20132010<ref name=\"Work Less Party Deregistered\">{{cite web|title=Deregistration of Western Block Party|url=http://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=pol&dir=par&document=index&lang=e#wlp|publisher=Elections Canada}}</ref>\n* [[The Bridge Party of Canada]] (David Berlin), 2015\u20132017<ref>http://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=pol&dir=par&document=index&lang=e#bridge</ref>\n* [[Canada Party (2015)|Canada Party]] (II) (Jim Pankiw) 2015\u20132016<ref>http://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=pol&dir=par&document=index&lang=e#canpar</ref>\n* Seniors Party of Canada (Margaret Leigh Fairbairn), 2014\u20132016<ref>http://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=pol&dir=par&document=index&lang=e#senior</ref>\n\n== Unofficial designations and parties who never ran candidates ==\nThe following parties do not appear on the federal election archive.<ref>https://lop.parl.ca/sites/ParlInfo/default/en_CA/ElectionsRidings/Elections</ref> They either did not run candidates in any election or ran candidates as independents.\n* [[Aboriginal Peoples Party of Canada]] (founded in 2005)\n* [[Absolutely Absurd Party]] (founded in 2003)\n* [[United Canadian Socialist Party]] (being launched in 2016)\n* [[Action Canada]] (founded in 1971)\n* [[Canadian Clean Start Party]] (founded in 2000)\n* [[Canadian Democratic Movement]] (founded in 2000)\n* [[Canadian Labour Party]], 1917\u20131929\n* [[Canadian Party for Renewal]], 1993\n* [[Canadian Union of Fascists]], 1930s\n* {{lang|fr|[[Candidat lib\u00e9ral des \u00e9lecteurs]]}}, 1962\u20131963\n* [[Christian Credit Party]], 1982\u20131983\n* [[Christian Freedom Party of Canada]], c. 1988 \u2013 c. 1996 (an extension of the Social Credit Party)\n* [[Freedom Party of Canada]], founded 2001\n* Forward Canada Party, 1997\n* [[The Waffle|Movement for an Independent Socialist Canada]], 1974\n* [[National Alternative Party]] (founded in 2002)\n* [[National Party of Canada (1979)|National Party of Canada]] (I), 1979\u20131980s\n* [[New Capitalist Party]], 1965\n* [[James Sears|New Constitution Party of Canada]] (an unregistered party founded in 2015)\n* [[North American Labour Party]], 1970s\n* [[Parti national social chr\u00e9tien|National Unity Party]], 1938\u20131949\n* ''[[Parti Populaire des Putes]]'' (founded in 2000)\n* [[People's Co-operative Commonwealth Federation]] 1945\n* [[Ontario Party of Canada]] (founded in 2002)\n* [[Option Canada (political party)|Option Canada]] (founded in 1991)\n* [[Rest of Canada Party]] (founded in 2002)\n* [[Revolutionary Workers League (Canada)|Revolutionary Workers League]], 1977\u20131989\n* Revolutionary Workers Party, 1945\u20131953\n* Unity Party of Canada (founded in 2001)\n* [[Workers' Communist Party of Canada]], 1972\u20131980\n\n===Pre-confederation political parties===\n* [[Reform Party (pre-Confederation)|Reform Party]] (pre-Confederation)\n\n==Name changes==\n\n;Communist Party\nThe Communist Party of Canada changed its name multiple times in its history. It was founded as the Communist Party of Canada in 1921. From 1938 until 1943 its candidates ran under the banner Unity or United Progressive. In 1943 it adopted the name [[Labor-Progressive Party]]. It won one seat under this name in 1945. In 1959 it reverted to the name Communist Party of Canada and has kept that name to the present.\n\nThe Marxist\u2013Leninist Party of Canada unofficially uses the name \"Communist Party of Canada (Marxist\u2013Leninist)\", but Elections Canada does not allow it to be registered by that name because of potential confusion with the Communist Party of Canada.\n\n;Labour Party\nLabour Party candidates ran under numerous different designations:\n* Conservative-Labour (1872\u20131875)\n* Farmer Labour\n* Farmer-United Labour\n* Labour-Farmer\n* [[Liberal-Labour (Canada)|Liberal-Labour]] (1926\u20131968)\n* National Labour (1940)\n* United Farmers-Labour (1920)\n* United Farmers of Ontario-Labour (1919\u20131940)\n\n;Liberal Party\nDuring Robert Borden's coalition government of 1917\u20131920, the Liberal Party of Canada split into two groups: the [[Liberal\u2013Unionist]] who supported the coalition and the [[Laurier Liberals]] who opposed it.\n\n;Liberal-Progressive\nSome Liberal-Progressive candidates used the designations:\n*Liberal-Labour-Progressive or\n*National Liberal Progressive.\n\n;New Democratic Party\nThe Co-operative Commonwealth Federation used the name [[New Party (Canada)|New Party]] from 1958\u20131961 while it was transitioning to become the New Democratic Party. In French, the party used a literal translation of its name, ''F\u00e9d\u00e9ration du Commonwealth Coop\u00e9ratif'', from until 1955.\n\n;Progressive Conservative Party\nThe first Conservative Party used several different names during its existence:\n*[[Liberal-Conservative Party]] (some MPs until 1911),\n*[[Unionist Party (Canada)|Unionist Party]] (1917\u20131921),\n*[[National Liberal and Conservative Party]] (1920\u20131921),\n*National Government (1940),\n*[[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative Party]] (1942\u20132003)\n\nThe second (and current) Conservative Party of Canada was a merger of the Canadian Alliance and the Progressive Conservative Party.\n\n;Progressive Party and United Farmers\nSome candidates for the Progressive Party of Canada used United Farmer designations:\n*[[Farmer (Party)|Farmer]] (1925 & 1930),\n*[[United Farmers of Canada]],\n*[[United Farmers of Alberta]], or\n*[[United Farmers of Ontario]].\n\n;Rhinoceros Party\nThe first Rhinoceros Party disbanded in 1993. When it was revived in 2006 it used the name \"neorhino.ca\". The party changed its name to Rhinoceros Party in 2010.\n\n;Social Credit Party and ''Ralliement cr\u00e9ditiste''\nSome ''Ralliement cr\u00e9ditiste'' used the name ''Ralliement des cr\u00e9ditistes'' from 1963 to 1967. One candidate used the designation ''Candidats des \u00e9lecteurs'' in 1957 and 1958. Others used the name Union des \u00e9lecteurs, although this was never formally registered.\n\nIn the 1940 election, 17 candidates ran jointly with the Social Credit Party under the name [[New Democracy (Canada)|New Democracy]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada|Politics}}\n*[[Federal political financing in Canada]]\n*[[List of political parties in Canada]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Elections in Canada}}\n{{Canadian federal political parties}}\n{{Lists of political parties in Canada}}\n\n==External links==\n* https://www.elections.ca/content.aspx?section=pol&dir=par&document=index&lang=e\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Federal Political Parties In Canada}}\n[[Category:Canada politics-related lists|Political parties]]\n[[Category:Lists of political parties in Canada|*]]\n", "name_user": "Walter G\u00f6rlitz", "label": "safe", "comment": "Canadian English", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_federal_political_parties_in_Canada"}
{"title_page": "Smallegade", "text_new": "{{Infobox street\n| name            = Smallegade\n| native_name     = \n| image           = Smallegade 02.jpg\n| image_size      = 320px\n| caption         = \n| former_names    = \n| length_m        = 750\n| width           =\n| location        = [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n| quarter                 = [[Frederiksberg]]\n| postal_code     = 1619, 1859\n| metro                   = [[Frederiksberg Station|Frederiksberg]], [[Fasanvej Station|Fasanvej]] \n| coordinates     = {{coord|55|40|44.76|N|12|31|38.28|E}}\n| direction_a             = East\n| terminus_a              = [[Gammel Kongevej]]\n| direction_b             = West\n| terminus_b              = [[Peter Bangs Vej]]\n| junction                = \n}}\n\n'''Smallegade''' ([[literal translation|lit.]] \"Narrow Street\") is a busy shopping street in the central part of [[Frederiksberg]] in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. It runs from the Town Hall Square in the east to [[Nordre Fasanvej|Fasanvej]] in the west, along the north side of Frederiksberg Town Hall and [[Frederiksberg Park]], linking [[Gammel Kongevej]] with [[Peter Bangs Vej]]. On the other side of the Town Hall is '''Bredegade''' (literally \"Broad Street\"), now smaller than Smallegade, which after a while joins Smallegade at [[M\u00f8stings Hus]], an 18th-century country house-turned-exhibitions space, which overlooks a small pond.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Smallegade.jpg|thumb|left|Smallegade viewed from [[All\u00e9gade]] in about 1800]]\n[[Image:Smallegade by Heinrich Johan Barby.jpg|thumb|Smallegade seen from Falkoner All\u00e9 in c. 1890. The house to the left has not yet been demolished to make way for the new Town Hall]]\n[[Image:Smallegade (1899).jpg|thumb|Smallegade in 1899]]\nIt is believed that Bredegade was the main street of Solbjerg, a village inhabited by Dutch farmers until the 1620s when it was shut down by [[Christian IV of Denmark|Christian IV]]. Smallegade was also one of the original \"Dutch\" streets but more open than Bredegade, with fields on its north side in between the scattered buildings.\n\nA brickyard was found at the far end of Smallegade until the 17th century. The Brickyard House (''Teglv\u00e6rksg\u00e5rden'') survived until 1890 when it was demolished. On a neighbouring site, Nobel opened a tobacco Factory in 1860. Eight years later that site was taken over by the faience manufactury [[Aluminia]]. They build a large factory complex where they were joined by the [[Royal Copenhagen|Royal Porcelain Manufactury]] in 184.\n\nBefore the Town Hall was built in the 1940s, its site was home to a neighbourhood with some 30 houses of which many dated from the 18th century.<ref name=Stadsarkivet>{{cite web|url=http://stadsarkivet.frederiksberg.dk/sites/stadsarkivet/files/attached/rundt_paa_det_historiske_frederiksberg_til_hjemmeside.pdf|title=Bredegade og Smallegade|language=Danish|publisher=Frederiksberg Stadsarkiv|accessdate=2013-07-21}}</ref>\n\n==Notable buildings and residents==\nThe most distinctive building in Smallegade is [[M\u00f8stings Hus]] which is located on the other side of a small pond (Andebakkedammen, \"Duck Stream Pond\"), which is believed to be the former village pond in Medieval Solbjerg. The house was built in 1800 and for 27 years served as summer residence for J.S. M\u00f8sting.  It was originally located on another site in Smallegade but dismantled in 1959 and rebuilt in its current location in 1976. It is now used as an exhibition space.<ref name=Stadsarkivet/>\n\n[[Image:Porcel\u00e6nshaven 1.jpg|thumb|200px|Porcel\u00e6nshaven]]\nBredegade boasts some other examples of 18th century country houses. No. 11 was built in the 1790s and was for a while owned by Prime Minister P.G. Bang. Ot is today used by the Municipality. No. 13 was built in 1805 by master carpenter Boye Junge. The widow after Carl\nHassager, a pastor converted into a hall of residence for ten students in 1897.<ref name=Stadsarkivet/>\n\n[[Image:Copenhagen Ceramics.JPG|thumb|200px|left|The building where Copenhagen Ceramics is based]]\nRoyal Copenhagen retired their production site in 2004. It has now been transformed into a [[mixed-use development]], now known as [[Porcel\u00e6nshaven]] (literally \"Porcelain Garden\"),  which retains many of the original factory buildings, including a landmark chimney, which is visible from the street.\n\nCopenhagen Ceramics at No. 46 is an exhibition space dedicated to temporary exhibitions of Danish ceramic art. It was opened by a group of artists in 2012 and is located in a courtyard away from the street.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b.dk/bolig/nyt-keramik-galleri|title=Nyt keramik-galleri|publisher=Berlingske|accessdate=2013-07-21}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nThe first part of the street is served by the [[Frederiksberg Station|Frederiksberg]] [[Copenhagen Metro]] station. The far end of the street is served by [[Fasanvej Station|Fasanvej]] metro station.\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Kjeld Petersen]] (1920-1962), actor, lived at No. 35 in 1958 \u20131962.\n\n==Cultural references==\nIn the first seasons of the [[TV2 (Denmark)|TV2]] sitcom ''[[Klovn]]'', Casper ([[Casper Christensen]]) and Frank ([[Frank Hvem]]) works out of an office in the Rialto Building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://danskefilm.dk/lokation.php?id=1841|title=Rialto-bygningen|language=Danish|publisher=danskefilm.dk|accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Frederiksberg All\u00e9]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Smallegade}}\n* [http://www.copenhagenceramics.com/ Copenhagen Ceramics]\n* [http://moestingshus.frederiksberg.dk/ M\u00f8stings Hus]\n\n{{Frederiksberg, Copenhagen}}\n\n{{coord|55.6791|N|12.5273|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Streets in Frederiksberg]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox street\n| name            = Smallegade\n| native_name     = \n| image           = Smallegade 02.jpg\n| image_size      = 320px\n| caption         = \n| former_names    = \n| length_m        = 750\n| width           =\n| location        = [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n| quarter                 = [[Frederiksberg]]\n| postal_code     = 1619, 1859\n| metro                   = [[Frederiksberg Station|Frederiksberg]], [[Fasanvej Station|Fasanvej]] \n| coordinates     = {{coord|55|40|44.76|N|12|31|38.28|E}}\n| direction_a             = East\n| terminus_a              = [[Gammel Kongevej]]\n| direction_b             = West\n| terminus_b              = [[Peter Bangs Vej]]\n| junction                = \n}}\n\n'''Smallegade''' ([[literal translation|lit.]] \"Narrow Street\") is a busy shopping street in the central part of [[Frederiksberg]] in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. It runs from the Town Hall Square in the east to [[Nordre Fasanvej|Fasanvej]] in the west, along the north side of Frederiksberg Town Hall and [[Frederiksberg Park]], linking [[Gammel Kongevej]] with [[Peter Bangs Vej]]. On the other side of the Town Hall is '''Bredegade''' (literally \"Broad Street\"), now smaller than Smallegade, which after a while joins Smallegade at [[M\u00f8stings Hus]], an 18th-century country house-turned-exhibitions space, which overlooks a small pond.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Smallegade.jpg|thumb|left|Smallegade viewed from [[All\u00e9gade]] in about 1800]]\n[[Image:Smallegade by Heinrich Johan Barby.jpg|thumb|Smallegade seen from Falkoner All\u00e9 in c. 1890. The house to the left has not yet been demolished to make way for the new Town Hall]]\n[[Image:Smallegade (1899).jpg|thumb|Smallegade in 1899]]\nIt is believed that Bredegade was the main street of Solbjerg, a village inhabited by Dutch farmers until the 1620s when it was shut down by [[Christian IV of Denmark|Christian IV]]. Smallegade was also one of the original \"Dutch\" streets but more open than Bredegade, with fields on its north side in between the scattered buildings.\n\nA brickyard was found at the far end of Smallegade until the 17th century. The Brickyard House (''Teglv\u00e6rksg\u00e5rden'') survived until 1890 when it was demolished. On a neighbouring site, Nobel opened a tobacco Factory in 1860. Eight years later that site was taken over by the faience manufactury [[Aluminia]]. They build a large factory complex where they were joined by the [[Royal Copenhagen|Royal Porcelain Manufactury]] in 184.\n\nBefore the Town Hall was built in the 1940s, its site was home to a neighbourhood with some 30 houses of which many dated from the 18th century.<ref name=Stadsarkivet>{{cite web|url=http://stadsarkivet.frederiksberg.dk/sites/stadsarkivet/files/attached/rundt_paa_det_historiske_frederiksberg_til_hjemmeside.pdf|title=Bredegade og Smallegade|language=Danish|publisher=Frederiksberg Stadsarkiv|accessdate=2013-07-21}}</ref>\n\n==Notable buildings and residents==\nThe most distinctive building in Smallegade is [[M\u00f8stings Hus]] which is located on the other side of a small pond (Andebakkedammen, \"Duck Stream Pond\"), which is believed to be the former village pond in Medieval Solbjerg. The house was built in 1800 and for 27 years served as summer residence for J.S. M\u00f8sting.  It was originally located on another site in Smallegade but dismantled in 1959 and rebuilt in its current location in 1976. It is now used as an exhibition space.<ref name=Stadsarkivet/>\n\n[[Image:Oorcel\u00e6nshaven 1.JPG|thumb|200px|Porcel\u00e6nshaven]]\nBredegade boasts some other examples of 18th century country houses. No. 11 was built in the 1790s and was for a while owned by Prime Minister P.G. Bang. Ot is today used by the Municipality. No. 13 was built in 1805 by master carpenter Boye Junge. The widow after Carl\nHassager, a pastor converted into a hall of residence for ten students in 1897.<ref name=Stadsarkivet/>\n\n[[Image:Copenhagen Ceramics.JPG|thumb|200px|left|The building where Copenhagen Ceramics is based]]\nRoyal Copenhagen retired their production site in 2004. It has now been transformed into a [[mixed-use development]], now known as [[Porcel\u00e6nshaven]] (literally \"Porcelain Garden\"),  which retains many of the original factory buildings, including a landmark chimney, which is visible from the street.\n\nCopenhagen Ceramics at No. 46 is an exhibition space dedicated to temporary exhibitions of Danish ceramic art. It was opened by a group of artists in 2012 and is located in a courtyard away from the street.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b.dk/bolig/nyt-keramik-galleri|title=Nyt keramik-galleri|publisher=Berlingske|accessdate=2013-07-21}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nThe first part of the street is served by the [[Frederiksberg Station|Frederiksberg]] [[Copenhagen Metro]] station. The far end of the street is served by [[Fasanvej Station|Fasanvej]] metro station.\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Kjeld Petersen]] (1920-1962), actor, lived at No. 35 in 1958 \u20131962.\n\n==Cultural references==\nIn the first seasons of the [[TV2 (Denmark)|TV2]] sitcom ''[[Klovn]]'', Casper ([[Casper Christensen]]) and Frank ([[Frank Hvem]]) works out of an office in the Rialto Building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://danskefilm.dk/lokation.php?id=1841|title=Rialto-bygningen|language=Danish|publisher=danskefilm.dk|accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Frederiksberg All\u00e9]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Smallegade}}\n* [http://www.copenhagenceramics.com/ Copenhagen Ceramics]\n* [http://moestingshus.frederiksberg.dk/ M\u00f8stings Hus]\n\n{{Frederiksberg, Copenhagen}}\n\n{{coord|55.6791|N|12.5273|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Streets in Frederiksberg]]\n", "name_user": "Hjart", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:Oorcel\u00e6nshaven 1.JPG\u2192File:Porcel\u00e6nshaven 1.jpgSpelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Smallegade"}
